'''David Laibman''' is Professor of Economics at Brooklyn College and the Graduate School, .  He received a Ph.D. in Economics in 1973 at the Graduate Faculty of the  in New York.<ref name="GC">[http://web.gc.cuny.edu/economics/pages/Faculty/laibman.html David Laibman]</ref> His dissertation, ''The Invariance Condition for Value-Price Transformation in a Linear, Non-Decomposable Two-Sector Model'', dealt with problems in Marxist value theory.<ref>See http://web.gc.cuny.edu/economics/FacultyDocs/laibman/RESUME.doc</ref> Laibman teaches , , and , at the undergraduate, masters, and doctoral levels at CUNY.<ref name="GC"/> 
He is the Editor of '''', a quarterly  journal now in its seventy first year of publication.<ref name="PA">[http://www.politicalaffairs.net/article/articleview/236/1/35/ From the Ashes of the Old: An Interview with David Laibman]</ref>
Laibman is the author of three books: ''Value, Technical Change and Crisis: Explorations in Marxist Economic Theory'' (1992), ''Capitalist Macrodynamics: A Systematic Introduction'' (1997), and ''Deep History: A Study in Social Evolution and Human Potential'' (2007).<ref name="GC"/> 
He is also a fingerstyle guitarist, especially its application to the  music of the early twentieth century. With , Laibman recorded ''The New Ragtime Guitar for Folkways'' in 1970.  His solo album, ''Classical Ragtime Guitar'', was released by '''' in 1980.<ref>[http://www.om28.com/press/pioneer.htm Eric Schoenberg]</ref>  He has just issued a DVD, ''Guitar Artistry of David Laibman'' .